---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="About — Pablo Corzo" theme="dark">
  <section class="shell pt-[46px]">
    <p class="t-label text-accent-text">About</p>
    <h1 class="t-title font-edo mt-[18px] max-w-[32ch]">
      My <span class="text-accent-text">Spaghetti-Shaped</span> Journey<span class="text-[var(--accent-alt)]">.</span>
    </h1>
  </section>

  <div class="shell">
    <div class="prose-article no-dropcap mx-[15px] pt-12">
       <p>
        I came up as both an engineer and a designer. The engineering side runs through
        industrial, process, and mechanical engineering, and through front-end development.
        The design side comes inherently and from a BFA in web design and interactive media.
      </p>
<blockquote>
      <p>
        My résumé looks like I lost a bet. Constantly deciding I'd like to be bad at
        something new for a while. This has worked out better than it sounds!
      </p>
</blockquote>
      <p>
        Design and engineering are usually treated as opposites. Left vs right brain. One is supposed to care how
        a thing feels. The other how it works. I never treated them as a choice between two
        careers (well not true, I did earlier on until I realized they could co-exist). Both have run through my work ever since and influence my connective
        thinking every day. Design, to me, has almost nothing to do with taste. It's the
        discipline of deciding what a thing is before you decide what it looks like. Most
        bad design isn't ugly. It's undecided, doubtful. Somebody skipped the part where you
        say out loud what this is for, who it's for, and what it refuses to do, and then
        they picked a style to cover the silence. The part I love is the deciding. 
Engineering gave me four different ways to see the same thing. 
<ul><li>Industrial engineering taught me that the bottleneck is never where people say it is. </li>
<li>Process engineering taught me that every output has a set of conditions that produced it, so
        if you don't like the output, arguing with it is a waste of a perfectly good
        afternoon. </li>
<li>Mechanical engineering taught me tolerance: nothing is exact, everything
        has slop in it, and the good designs stay standing anyway.</li>
<li>Front-end development taught me the fastest lesson of the four, which is that you are wrong and the
        browser will tell you in roughly four seconds, without softening it, in front of
        everyone.</li></ul>
      </p>

      <p>
        My path moved from there into data, and later into leading. Data didn't feel like a
        departure. It felt like finally getting the instrument I'd been missing. I'd spent
        years building things with no real way to know whether any of it worked, which meant
        opinions filled the gap, and the loudest opinion won. I have never enjoyed losing an
        argument to volume. Measurement is just the engineering habit pointed at a product
        instead of a machine: define the thing, define what "working" means, then go find
        out. Same discipline. Better tools. Fewer meetings that end in a shrug. Leading
        turned out to be the strangest of the four, because almost none of it is doing. It's
        saying the unglamorous sentence in the room where everyone would rather move on. The
        rest of the job is absorbing ambiguity so the people around you get to do focused
        work instead of guessing, and nobody claps for that part either.
      </p>

      <p>
        From the outside, my path looked like spaghetti, and was incredibly misunderstood as
        'being lost or undecided' rather than curiosity. Design, engineering, data, product, all "running" in different
        directions with no clean line through them. But the strands were not random. They
        were bending toward the same point. The point is definition. All four disciplines
        are the same practice wearing different clothes: refusing to move until you know
        what the thing actually is. Design defines what it's for. Engineering defines what
        it can survive. Data defines what counts as working. Leadership defines who gets to
        say. </p>

<blockquote>
      <p>So I no longer explain the zigzag. It was never four
        careers with a person stuck between them. It was one practice that took four
        disciplines to learn. Which means the next thing probably won't look like a straight
        line either, and at this point I'd be suspicious if it did.</p>
</blockquote>

      <p class="t-standfirst font-ui mt-2 text-muted">
        For the working version of all this — what I do, and where I can help —
        <a href="/about/profile" class="text-accent-text">see the profile →</a>
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
